          <h2 class="h2-title">
            The Bedrock of Investment: Upholding the Sanctity of Contracts in
            Nigeria's Energy Sector
          </h2>
          <div class="blog-detail-text-box">
            <p>
              Nigeria's energy sector serves as the primary engine of its
              national economy, attracting significant long-term,
              capital-intensive investment from both local and international
              players. The foundation upon which these monumental investments
              are built is not the physical assets themselves, but a core legal
              principle: the sanctity of contracts.
            </p>
            <p>
              Agreements such as Production Sharing Contracts (PSCs), Joint
              Venture Agreements, and Power Purchase Agreements often span
              decades. Investors commit billions of dollars based on the
              assurance that the terms of these contracts will be honoured and
              enforced throughout their lifecycle. When the government and its
              agencies demonstrate a steadfast commitment to upholding these
              agreements, it sends a powerful signal of stability and
              predictability to the global market, fostering the confidence
              required for continued investment and economic development.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="blog-detail-text-box">
